column44: Notes

An additional parameter was added for the respiration model #1 as explained in Klumb et al. (2003). This parameter (RK5) allows for the inclusion of a temperature effect on swimming at temperatures higher than RTL. Models not requiring the use of this parameter can set RK5 to 0. Additionally, the consumption model parameters published in Stewart & Binkowski (1986) for young of the year were used here; RA parameter was changed to reflect standard metabolism; RTO and RTL were set to 0.
Respiration model parameters were taken from Rudstam 1989.
CB value was changed to -0.32 for coregonids that reach large size

column44: Changed FB, FG, UB, UG from 0 to NA. "Activity" assumed to be zero (i.e., activity multipler of 1), so RTO, RTM, RTL, RK1, RK4, ACT AND BACT all set to zero.  Measured pred. EDs listed as a note in the ED column

Changed ACT to 0. In REQ 1 ACTIVITY calculation does not use ACT as a direct multiplier (paper has ACT+1 as a direct multiplier).  To achieve that in our REQ 1 RTO must be set to zero, and/or RK1 and ACT must be set to zero.  Best to make ACT 0 so users don't think setting it to 1 will get them an Activity multiplier of 1.  SDA, FA and UA were borrowed from alewife model.

SDA, FA and UA were borrowed from alewife model.

No value was given for SDA (in initial parameter table, or in the paper); It was thus set to 0.172, typical of salmonid models. No egestion or excretion eq. or parameters in paper; Values from Rand 1993 were used, which came from Stewart et al. 1983.  Note: Cmax experiments were done with dry artificial food.
Railsback and Rose updated Rand's rainbow trout model using newly published data for C and R, they (correctly) used values of 25 and 22.5 for CTO and CTM respectively.
Changed FB, FG, UB, UG from 0 to NA

In REQ 1 ACTIVITY calculation does not use ACT as a direct multiplier, but in this paper they measured routine R and considered it representative, so we need a constant multiplier of 1.  To achieve that in REQ 1 RTO must be set to zero, and/or RK1 and ACT must be set to zero.
Tarvainen et al. express excretion as a fraction of C, as originally in Elliott 1976, not of C-F as we have it.  So currently this formulation doesn't exactly emulate their model.
column62: NOTE:  I don't see the same problem here; Tarvainen et al use equation 2 for excreation and egestion, and for excretion, U is calculated from assimilated energy because (C-F) is included in the equation.

column44: Note: The consumption parameter in this model (i.e., CA value) is derived as dry weight food consumed per gram of predator wet weight and will affect the calculations in the model because prey energy density is entered as J/g wet wt. The original paper fed crayfish alignate, but we could'nt find a dry:wet conversion for this; All parameters borrowed or estimated.  Changed RK1 and ACT to 0. In REQ 1 ACTIVITY calculation does not use ACT as a direct multiplier (paper has ACT+1 as a direct multiplier).  To achieve that in our REQ 1 RTO must be set to zero, and/or RK1 and ACT must be set to zero.  Best to make ACT 0 so users don't think setting it to 1 will get them an Activity multiplier of 1.  Authors use Equation 3 for Egestion, with no temperature or ration size effect (FB and FG = 0).  But they use Equation 1 for Excretion.
Author expressed UA as a fraction of C; UA ajusted for (C-F); changed their 0.0253 to 0.0300.
SDA is adjusted from proportion of C = 0.23 to proportion of C-F = 0.2386.

SDA is adjusted from proportion of C = 0.15 to proportion of C-F = 0.1546.  UA is adjusted from proportion of C = 0.15 to proportion of C-F = 0.1546.  Paper gives conflicting valuses for ED (5190 J/g, 1224 cal/g); source was in cal/g, so value here (5120 J/g) is based on that (assuming 4.184 J/cal).  RA in paper (0.0105) is in grams of lamprey; here converted to grams of O2 (0.00396) using oxycal. coeff. of 13,560 J/g O2.

UA is adjusted from proportion of C = 0.079 to proportion of C-F = 0.08817.  Authors use REQ 1, but with an activity multiplier of 2.1.  We achieve this using REQ 2 with RTO set to 0.7419 (i.e., ln 2.1) and RK1 and ACT to 0; that makes ACTIVITY = 2.1.

Most parameters are borrowed from Chinook, Coho and Brown Trout.  Authors mention using the first part of the weight-dependent energy density equation for salmon, but not the second part above a weight cutoff.  The weight cutoff, alpha2 and Beta2 values were borrowed from Chinook salmon model and may not be applicable to Steelhead.

UA was adjusted for (C-F); made RTO = LN(1.04) and RTL=RK4=0 and RK1=1 so VEL = 1 and ACTIVITY = EXP(RTO*VEL) = 1.04; CAUTION! This model needs their correction factor!
I set RTL=RK1=ACT=RK4=RTO=0 so that ACTIVITY = 1 = EXP(RTO*VEL) for REQ=1.
